  "modules": [
    {
      "title": "AC values",
      "html": "<p>An alternating voltage V = V₀ sin(ωt) has:</p><ul><li><b>Peak value</b> V₀.</li><li><b>RMS value</b> V_rms = V₀/√2 ≈ 0.707 V₀.</li><li><b>Average over full cycle</b>: 0. Mean over half cycle = 2V₀/π ≈ 0.637 V₀.</li><li><b>Angular frequency</b> ω = 2πf. Period T = 1/f.</li></ul><p>Household meters read RMS; e.g. 240 V mains has V₀ ≈ 340 V.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "RMS of a 100 V peak AC?",
          "a": "100/√2 ≈ 70.7 V."
        },
        {
          "q": "Peak of a 220 V rms supply?",
          "a": "220·√2 ≈ 311 V."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Pure resistor, inductor, capacitor",
      "html": "<p><b>Pure resistor</b>: V and I in phase. Power dissipated = V_rms · I_rms.</p><p><b>Pure inductor</b>: V leads I by 90°. Inductive reactance X_L = 2πfL.</p><p><b>Pure capacitor</b>: I leads V by 90°. Capacitive reactance X_C = 1/(2πfC).</p><p>Pure L and C dissipate no real power on average.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Reactance of a 0.1 H inductor at 50 Hz?",
          "a": "X_L = 2π·50·0.1 ≈ 31.4 Ω."
        },
        {
          "q": "Reactance of a 10 μF capacitor at 50 Hz?",
          "a": "X_C = 1/(2π·50·10⁻⁵) ≈ 318 Ω."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Impedance and R-L-C circuits",
      "html": "<p>Series R-L-C impedance Z = √(R² + (X_L − X_C)²).</p><p>Phase angle: tan φ = (X_L − X_C)/R. Current I = V/Z.</p><p><b>Resonance</b> occurs when X_L = X_C → f₀ = 1/(2π√(LC)). At resonance Z = R (minimum), current maximum, and voltage across L and C cancel.</p><p>Power factor = cos φ = R/Z. Real power P = V_rms · I_rms · cos φ.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "R=8 Ω, X_L=10 Ω, X_C=4 Ω. Impedance?",
          "a": "Z = √(64+36)=10 Ω."
        },
        {
          "q": "Resonant frequency of L=0.1 H, C=10 μF?",
          "a": "f₀ = 1/(2π√(10⁻⁶)) = 159 Hz."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
